<font color="#FF0000">MERRY CHRISTMAS</font><br>
<tt>Sat Dec 13 17:33:00 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Thanks for the Christmas reminiscence in Vietnam Cook.   We all tried to make the holiday special, and we had to be a bit more imaginative than would have been necessary in the States.  I am from the Northeast.  Every Christmas was cold and there was snow on the ground.  Somehow, it just didn't feel much like Christmas in Vietnam.  But we tried too.<br><br>
The patients who were well enough to get up and go to the rec center cut out hundreds of paper snowflakes which were hung from the ceiling in the quonset huts for decorations.  There was some kind of tree but I can't remember for the life of me what it actually was.  The day before Christmas three of us Red Cross women went to one of the firebases to help out the real donut dollies deliver ditty bags.  Every soldier in country was suppose to get a ditty bag for Christmas from the American people who made contributions through the Red Cross  (some men told me they didn't get one. I don't know why.).  The ditty bags were cloth bags made out of the same blue pinstripe cloth that our Red Cross uniforms were made from.  I don't remember much of what went in them. I believe there was some writing paper, maybe a comb.  The big thing was WD-40 spray that helped keep your weapons firing. Many of the ditty bags found their way into Vietnamese girls hands as gifts from soldiers ( the girls apparently liked to use the pull string bags for purses.)  <br><br>
On Christmas Eve and into Christmas morning, hospital staff went from ward to ward singing Christmas carols.  One of the Sargeants looked like the tubby old man himself when he put on a Santa claus outfit then went from patient to patient with Christmas stockings for all.  We had a kool-aid and cookie party at the rec center, and one of the staff members played Christmas carols on the piano in the center.  But the most memorable part of the whole time for me was when the men were able to make phone calls home.  A MARS station was set up at the rec center with ham radios (I don't remember what the initials MARS stand for ).  Two ham radio operators were required for each call which would be made over open air waves to the United States where the call was then made home on a regular MA bell phone.  After finishing each statement, you would have to say &quot;over&quot; since a switch had to be open when transmitting and turned off to receive.  It was confusing and humorous when callers would forget to follow the transmission rules, or say something that shouldn't be said over open lines. Many families were pleasantly surprized by the calls.  A number of volunteeers in the states deserved credit for making it possible for a number of soldiers in Vietnam to talk to their family that Christmas. For the lucky callers, that meant so much to be able to speak to family half-way around the world and I was glad to be able to help make it happen.<br><br>
Christmas was emotionally tough in a war torn country and without our families.. but it seemed to me that we formed our own family units when our biological ones weren't there.  We still honored the season in their own way.<br><br>
Merry Christmas this year to all my brothers.  Isn't it good to be home.
<p><code>--   (Class Lass) </code><p>


